Downloading copyrighted music via peer to peer may not be moral, but neither has been the monopoly labels have held on the price we pay, or the way people are able to get, music. What ability does the general public have allowing them to take a stance against that? Not buy the CD's? But its the music they want, not all this other political shit. <br>
<br>
 If people are losing their jobs as a result of this then it is most likely because the companies in questions, especially any of them that are incorporated and publicly traded, are not achieving budgeted margins as a result of this change (percentage of growth over prior year, budgeted cash flows, blahblahblah), so yes, people objecting IS having an impact, but it is the individual company that chooses HOW they contend with that. Reduction of staffing is always a quick fix catch all to that problem. Some of these companies are also stuck in the middle, if they could do it differently they would...but the most powerful ones are not-they are the ones setting the examples and establishing the practices for others to use. And if they refuse to adapt, then the smaller ones WILL be hurt, because smaller ones cannot establish a standard usually to impact the bigger picture.<br>
<br>
Im not saying p2p with music is right, -it does utterly defeat the intent of copyright as it exists at this time-,I am saying it is something that was bound to happen given a situation that was abused by the very companies that are now being hurt. There was a need, and someone filled it. I think at this point, due to the extreme nature of the RIAA's actions, that yes, they probably just made the problem even worse, because now people will knowingly and happily go about finding ways to do it. It is a problem that needed addressed, but they kicked a bees nest doing it the way they have.<br>
<br>
<br>
Lich Vrex Aeternus<br>
65 playgirl lizard<br>
